<TITLE> Cambodia charges Russian businessman with child abuse </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PHNOM PENH, March 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A Cambodian court charged on Tuesday a Russian businessman overseeing a $300 million tourism investment project with sexual abuse of a 14-year-old girl. Alexander Trofimov, who attended the three-hour hearing in jeans and a shirt and without handcuffs, denied the charge and said he had never met the girl, who testified that she had been paid $100 after being abused four times. The girl told the court she was lured by a female pimp from the capital, Phnom Penh, to the coastal province of Sihanoukville, where Trofimov's company signed a deal in 2006 to build a major tourist resort on Koh Pos, or Snake Island. Trofimov, 41, has been in prison in Phnom Penh since his arrest in October, and could be sentenced to up to 20 years in the southeast Asian nation if found guilty. The presiding judge is expected to announce his verdict on March 14, court officials sa
